Peel and chop the @carrot{1}(peeled), @garlic clove{1}(finely chopped) and @red onion{1/2}(diced as finely as possible). Finely chop the @celery stick{1}(finely chopped). 

> Tip: Whizz in a food processor if you have one. 

Peel and roughly chop the @parsnip{1}(peeled and chopped into 2cm cubes). Finely chop the @spring onion{2}(finely chopped) and roughly chop the @dried apricots{3}(roughly chopped).

Heat @oil{1%tbsp} in a #non-stick frying pan{} on medium-low heat. Cook the finely diced carrot, garlic, onion, celery and the parsnip for about ~{8%minutes}. 

> Tip: You want to cook the mixture until it is soft and be sure not to let it brown off.

Sprinkle on @salt{1/4%tsp} and half the @Kabsa spice{1}(half). Add the chopped apricots, give everything a quick stir and put a lid on the stew for ~{5%minutes}. When the vegetables have softened add the @chopped tomatoes{1%can} and @water{200%ml}. 

> Tip: If your stew is drying out a little, turn the heat to low and add a dash of water.

== Meatballs ==

For the meatballs, thoroughly mix the spring onions into the @lamb mince{250%g}. Mix in @salt{1/4%tsp}, @ground black pepper{1/4%tsp} and the remaining Kabsa spice.

Take 1 tsp of the lamb mixture at a time and roll it into a little ball. 

> Tip: Keep a cup of water to clean your fingers while you make the meatballs. Tip: You want to keep the meatballs small, so we recommend a helper to speed up the process.

Heat @oil{1%tbsp} in a non-stick frying pan on medium-high heat. Cook the meatballs for a couple of mins on each side until they are browned off. When the meatballs are browned off, drain the oil and rest them on #kitchen towel{}.

== Couscous ==

In a #pot{}, add @water{250%ml}(boiling) together with @chicken stock pot{1/2}. Add in your @couscous{3/4%cup} and cover the pot with a lid. Take off the heat and leave to rest for ~{5%minutes}. 

> Tip: Be exact with the amount of water to prevent soggy couscous!

== To Serve ==

Roughly chop the @coriander{3}(roughly chopped). Fluff up your couscous with a #fork{}. Stir the meatballs gently into the stew. Serve the stew on top of the couscous with a sprinkle of coriander.